		<a name="16150"></a>
		<img src="icon_posticon.gif" border="0" hspace="3"><font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="1">Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;03/31/2002&nbsp;:&nbsp; 23:58:33</font>

		&nbsp;<a href="pop_profile.asp?mode=display&id=3106"><img src="icon_profile.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Show Profile" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>
        
			&nbsp;<a href="JavaScript:openWindow('pop_mail.asp?id=3106')"><img src="icon_email.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Email Poster" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&REPLY_ID=16150&TOPIC_ID=2113&FORUM_ID=2&CAT_ID=1&Forum_Title=General+Discussions&Topic_Title=BL+pets+look+out+for+nerf+bat%2E&M="><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        <hr noshade size="1">
        
        <font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2"> I'll add my comments because I have a 52 bst.</P><P>First the comments about the BL themselves are true.  They are a weak melee class.  They have about the same melee ability as a bard except they are a leather restricted class.  Their armor is far and few between and rather weak.  Nearly all of it is very low AC and marginal stats.</P><P>The BL is a hybrid so they have the same penalties as the other hybrids.</P><P>The BL pet is a nice pet.  No question there.  The BL does not have a pet cheal spell other then to use their pet level buff spell which effectively cheals the pet.  This means that player is exploiting a known bug to do the cheal.  Verant knows about this and has stated that they will be fixing it.  This is a no brainer.  I never use the exploit.</P><P>The BL pet is slightly less powerful then a necro pet at like levels.  In fact the max damage, all the way to the top of the line pet is 55.  The BST must also summon a green pet and then buff it with a level spell and then buff it with haste, and then buff it with a proc.  While we necros cast our pet and they are born with their level and proc theirs starts weak and needs buffing or it is useless.  The BST pet requires no reagent.  When the BST zones all the buffs the pet had are lost and have to be redone.</P><P>Because the BST is a hybrid most of their mana goes into buffing or rebuffing to get the pet to a workable level.  Because the pet zones and reverts back to a green pet the pet can and does become a liability.  They tend to roam when first zoning in and they will agro mobs nearby.</P><P>The HP of the pet are no different the the HP for a comparable level pet for the necro or magi.  The bst pet does double attack and dual wield.  The BST themselves are limited to dual wield which is one of the reasons for their non-stellar performance without a pet.</P><P>On raids the bst has virutally no role.  Their spells are overwritten by everyone and they are no better at surviving a hit then a shaman is on uber encounters.  Since they are limited to leather they have a serious limitation on their ability to take blows.  The shaman can heal themselves sufficiently, and have a 200 defense skill at 60.</P><P>The main bst buffs at 60 don't add anything to the raid and have stacking issues with vog and potg.</P><P>Other then that the bst can sufficiently solo at the lower levels.  Downtime is about the same as for everyone.  They have no mana regen, no hp regen (except ranger level heal spells).</P><P>What sets the bst aside from the other pet classes is that the pet can be healed in a major way.  Verant created pet heal spells especially for the bst pets.  But, none of them are cheal spells except when using the known bug as an exploit.  The bst is distinguished by the fact that he can heal his pet well even if he can't heal or buff others well.  The bst buffs are too low level and too short duration to be of any real value especially in exp groups.  The only positive thing that could be said is that they are better then nothing.</P><P>The level 60 bst slow spell,whch is 50%, drops off the highest of high level mobs.  The only one that I've seen dropped was off tunare. This doesn't mean that others don't drop the spell.</P><P>The slow spell is as resisted as any other spell cast by any other class.  Comparatively the bst slow spell is highly resited compared to ebolt or any other dot you may cast.  There are times when on blue con mobs you have to cast the slow spell 4-6 times just to get it to take. This adds alot of agro.</P><P>The bst does have a slight AC bonus like the monk has being a leather wearing melee class.  They do not have the monk weight penalty.</P><P>Most level 60 bst that I have read talk about the bst say they are without a role at the high end.  Anyone reading the spell list and looking at the skills knows this without even having played one.</P><P>I guess more slowers at a raid couldn't hurt.  I often use my ranger's epics to slow mobs when the shaman die to mob agro.  But I won't say the bst is more survivable then the shaman because he isn't.  The shaman, at a comparable level will always be better equipped because there's just more chain gear out there then there is leather that benefits the bst.  The only thing I can honestly say about having more slowers at an event is that even though you have more slowers you more then likely have more dead slowers.</P><P> <a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height=15 width=15 border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
      </tr>

